<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-07-25T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-07-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="661" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d661">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 838.111/126.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Port au Prince</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-07-25">
                                    <hi rend="italic">July 25, 1913</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The President of Haiti says that, in accord with the Act of 1903, no
                            persons of Syrian origin can come to Haiti and remain permanently. The
                            President has, however, agreed to permit naturalized American citizens
                            of Syrian origin who represent American commercial interests to enter
                            Haiti on the business of their firms if they remain only a few months
                            and if their citizenship and their connection with American commercial
                            concerns are certified by the Department of State or the American
                            Legation.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Furniss</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>